About---

ECLIPSE — COMPLETE PROJECT DOCUMENTATION
Full Vision, Architecture, Roadmap & Philosophy

—

1. PROJECT OVERVIEW



Eclipse is a next-generation Android browser designed to give mobile users complete control over their browsing experience. Unlike traditional browsers that focus only on navigation and privacy, Eclipse combines browsing, intelligent search, deep customization, widgets, AI assistance, and community-driven design into one unified platform.

Eclipse is not intended to be a Chrome alternative or a lightweight privacy browser clone. It is designed to become a fully customizable digital space where users control their layout, search experience, visual identity, and interaction style — all without paid tiers or locked features.

Core Mission:

Full customization on mobile (comparable to PC-level flexibility)

Premium experience with zero paid features

Privacy-first architecture

Gradual evolution toward independent search infrastructure

Community-driven creative ecosystem


Tagline: “Eclipse — Not just a browser. Your world.”

—

2. CURRENT STATE OF DEVELOPMENT



Current build status: Eclipse Dawn 0.1 (Polish Phase)

The first uploaded file contains the current working browser codebase. The goal in this phase is refinement and stabilization — not feature expansion.

Current fixes and improvements include:

Redesigned premium splash screen

Dynamic greeting text (Good Morning/Afternoon/Evening/Night Explorer)

Horizontal scrolling news section with refresh

Bottom navigation bar stability

Home button alignment fix

Expanded and structured menu

Proper Eclipse logo integration


At this stage, Eclipse functions as a working browser using external search engines. The next milestone is integrating Eclipse’s own search UI powered by SearXNG.

—

3. CORE ARCHITECTURE



Platform: Android application using Android WebView as the browsing engine.

Hybrid structure:

Native Android layer (Kotlin/Java)

UI layer using HTML/CSS/JavaScript inside WebView

Backend integrations for search and APIs


Technology stack:

WebView for rendering websites

SearXNG (self-hosted) for aggregated search results

Groq API (Llama models) for AI Answer Mode

OpenWeatherMap API for weather-reactive UI

NASA API for space widgets

Supabase (future) for community storage

Cloudflare Workers (future) for backend logic

Local storage for user settings and layouts


Zero cost philosophy: All services must remain within free-tier limits or open-source infrastructure.

—

4. DESIGN REQUIREMENTS



The UI must feel premium, handcrafted, and intentional.

It must not:

Feel AI-generated

Feel template-based

Feel “vibe-coded”

Feel generic or rushed


The UI must:

Have smooth, controlled animations

Use intentional easing curves

Use refined spacing

Use depth and layering

Include scroll-triggered animations

Have subtle motion polish

Feel cohesive and alive


A full Glassy UI option must be implemented:

Backdrop blur

Transparency

Light refraction feel

Depth layering

Adjustable blur intensity

No visual glitches


Animation priority: Smoothness and polish are more important than app size or code brevity.

Development rule: Slow, precise, tested after every major change. No rushing.

—

5. SEARCH SYSTEM VISION



Phase 1 — SearXNG Integration

Self-hosted SearXNG instance

Results displayed in custom Eclipse card UI

Four tabs: All, News, Images, Videos

Cards include title, URL, description

Tap opens result inside Eclipse WebView

No crashes allowed


Phase 2 — Search Modes

Explore Mode (comparison-style browsing)

Answer Mode (AI-generated summary via Groq)

Deep Mode (research-style, full source visibility)

Quick Mode (instant open)


Phase 3 — Special Cards

Wikipedia summary

Reddit discussions

News with images

Image grid

Inline calculator

Weather inline

Currency converter inline


Long-Term Goal: Gradually build Eclipse’s own search index, starting small and expanding to full independence over 3–4 years.

—

