To integrate the provided components properly, the project must use a Next.js App Router setup with TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, and shadcn/ui structure. If the project does not already support this, initialize it using npx create-next-app@latest --typescript --tailwind --app, then run npx shadcn-ui@latest init to configure shadcn. During setup, ensure the components directory is set to components and the import alias is @/. Tailwind should already be configured through the Next.js setup, and global styles should live inside app/globals.css. The default and recommended location for reusable UI components in a shadcn project is /components/ui. If this folder does not exist, it must be created manually because shadcn follows a structured design system where base UI primitives are separated from feature-level components. This separation improves maintainability, reusability, and design consistency across the application.

All provided components must be placed inside /components/ui. The files splite.tsx, container-scroll-animation.tsx, and glowing-effect.tsx should be copied exactly into this folder. Dependency components such as card.tsx (shadcn card), spotlight.tsx (either aceternity or ibelick version), and any required helpers must also live in /components/ui unless they are utilities. Ensure lib/utils.ts contains the cn helper function used for class merging. After placing the files, install all required external dependencies using npm install framer-motion motion lucide-react @splinetool/runtime @splinetool/react-spline. These libraries power scroll animations, pointer-based glow effects, spline 3D rendering, and SVG icons.

The ContainerScroll component depends on framer-motion’s useScroll and useTransform hooks and requires no global provider. It accepts a titleComponent prop (string or ReactNode) and renders children inside a perspective-based animated card that rotates and scales based on scroll progress. It is responsive and detects mobile width to adjust scaling. The SplineScene component lazy loads a Spline 3D scene using Suspense and requires a valid Spline scene URL passed through the scene prop. The GlowingEffect component uses pointer movement and the Motion library’s animate function to create a dynamic gradient border glow. It is controlled via props like blur, spread, proximity, borderWidth, and disabled. It requires no external state management.

Images used in demos should be replaced with valid Unsplash URLs or optimized using Next.js <Image />. Icons should be imported from lucide-react. These components are best used in landing pages, hero sections, feature showcases, or premium UI sections where motion and interactivity enhance user experience. No additional global providers are required, but ensure Tailwind dark mode is configured if using dark classes. Once dependencies are installed and files are placed correctly, the components are ready for use.



